1.2.1 Stateful API: persistent CVODE handles
--------------------------------------------

‘np_cvode’ is single-shot -- every call builds a fresh ‘cvode_mem’,
integrates, and tears down.  For event-driven loops (bouncing ball,
switched dynamics, hybrid controllers) the consumer pays the setup cost
on every segment, even though only the initial state changes between
them.  SUNDIALS' ‘CVodeReInit’ is designed for exactly this -- keep the
integrator alive, just reset the IC. The stateful API exposes it:

handle : np_cvode_create(f, vars, y0, t0, rtol, atol, method, events, max_steps, rootdir)$
[t_actual, y_state, events_during_step] : np_cvode_step(handle, t_target)$
np_cvode_reinit(handle, t_new, y_new)$
[t2, y2, evs2] : np_cvode_step(handle, next_target)$
np_cvode_close(handle)$

Each ‘np_cvode_step’ call advances the integrator from its current
internal state up to ‘t_target’, collecting any events along the way.
‘np_cvode_reinit’ discards the multistep history (correct after a
discrete state change) and resets the IC without rebuilding the linear
solver or reregistering events.

Resource lifecycle is two-tiered:

   • *Explicit close* (‘np_cvode_close’) -- frees the foreign resources
     immediately.  Recommended for hot loops or long-lived sessions.
   • *GC fallback* -- every handle returned by ‘np_cvode_create’ is
     wrapped in a struct with a finalizer registered via
     ‘trivial-garbage’.  If the user drops the reference without calling
     ‘np_cvode_close’, the finalizer runs at the next full GC and
     reclaims the resources.  Idempotent with explicit close, so calling
     close + later GC is safe.
   • *‘np_cvode_with_handle’* -- the canonical resource-safe pattern.
     Wraps ‘create + body + close’ in Common Lisp's ‘unwind-protect’, so
     the handle is always closed even if ‘body’ errors.  Maxima's own
     ‘unwind_protect’ has historically been unreliable for this; the
     wrapper sidesteps that.

result : np_cvode_with_handle(
  [f, vars, y0, t0, rtol, atol, method, events, max_steps, rootdir],
  lambda([h],
    /* use h freely; do whatever */
    final_value))$
/* h is closed by the time we get here, success or failure */

‘np_cvode_step’ returns ‘[t_actual, [y...], events_list]’ where
‘events_list’ has the same shape as the events list returned by
‘np_cvode’ (entries of ‘[t_event, [y...], [indices], [directions]]’).

